Most of the chemical diversity of wood (colour, fragrance and durability) is embedded in the extractives 
i.e.
the non-structural components that are solubilized by solvents with different polarities, and that include a diverse array of chemical families. In the case of the lipophilic soluble fraction extracted by non-polar solvents such as dichloromethane, hexane or petroleum ether, the chemical families include mainly fatty acids and alcohols, phytosterols, hydrocarbons and triterpenes (

; 

; 

).

Some of these compounds have received attention due to their potential interest as bioactive and functional molecules and to the possibility of integrating extractives recovery as a process step in biorefineries (

). Moreover, some wood lipophilic extractives may be a nuisance in pulp processing, because of equipment fouling and product staining (

; Sjostr ¨¨om and 

; 

).

Eucalyptus globulus
is a major pulpwood feedstock, similarly to other eucalypt species i.e .
E. urograndis , E. grandis , E. maidenii
and therefore extractives of their wood and forest residues have been researched both aiming at decreasing their effect in pulping as well as valorising them as value added chemicals (
;
). Most studies restricted the quantification and identification of the lipophilic extractives in
E. globulus
to only those present in higher amounts and without addressing the question of their variability (
; Guti´errez et al., 1999;
;
). In fact, the extractives are produced and accumulated along the tree’ s lifetime, and it is expected to find an intrinsic variability of extractives composition within or between trees. It is therefore foreseeable that the presence and proportion of specific compounds or chemical families will differ in different parts of the tree e.g. in sapwood and heartwood and at the different levels of stem height (
,
).

