163
) and madecassic acid (
164
). In barks, leaves and fruits of 

E. globulus

the presence of triterpenic acids such as betulonic, betulinic, ursolic, oleanolic, 3-acetylursolic and 3-acetyloleanolic acids has been reported (

, 

, 2011b, 2010). These compounds are interesting since have biological activities and can be used for example for medical applications (

).

The presence of other type of compounds ( Table 6 ) represents less than 5% of the total DCM extract ( Fig. 3 ), and includes α- tocopherol, ferulates, sitosteryl 3-β- D-glucopyranoside and lignans (pinoresinol, syringaresinol). The content of α- tocopherol (4.0 mg/g of extract corresponding to 114.5 mg /kg of wood) was higher than the values of 0.9–5.4 mg /kg of wood reported by
. Regarding the lignans identified, as far as we know, this is the first time that these compounds are identified in eucalypt. Potential new therapeutic agents of lignans are reported for the production of lignan-rich to prevention of chronic illness, such as certain types of cancers and cardiovascular disease (
).

